post_text: Thank you to everyone for your patience and support as months of work culminated in the safe return of students for the first day of the 2020-2021 school year. There was a lot to organize as we simultaneously launched a staggered return for in-person learning and the all-new Jefferson Virtual Academy. As we spend these first two weeks learning new routines, providing social emotional support, and finalizing schedule changes, we ask for your continued partnership. For those students who have changes, JCS staff will continue to update schedule information on LiveGrades and Google Classroom. Students who are on-site will receive their schedule on location the day they arrive so that the teaching staff can walk them through the process in person. This is a unique experience for everyone. No matter what the future holds, we continue to embrace the challenges ahead of us and remain committed to delivering the quality instruction and high academic performance you have come to expect for your children.

post_text: In response to new restrictions on crowd size issued by Governor Jim Justice, Jefferson County Schools must regretfully postpone the planned graduation ceremonies for the Class of 2020, which were originally set for Aug. 1. After investing a significant amount of staff time and effort to create a ceremony compliant with previous guidance, the Jefferson County Board of Education, along with Jefferson County Schools staff and administrators, share the immense disappointment felt by this resilient group of young people and their loved ones. Everyone remains committed to giving them the traditional, in-person graduation ceremony they deserve as soon as restrictions and guidance allow. Thank you for your patience and understanding. Updated information will be provided as it is received. We remain immeasurably proud of these graduates and their achievements.
text: In response to new restrictions on crowd size issued by Governor Jim Justice, Jefferson County Schools must regretfully postpone the planned graduation ceremonies for the Class of 2020, which were originally set for Aug. 1. After investing a significant amount of staff time and effort to create a ceremony compliant with previous guidance, the Jefferson County Board of Education, along with Jefferson County Schools staff and administrators, share the immense disappointment felt by this resilient group of young people and their loved ones. Everyone remains committed to giving them the traditional, in-person graduation ceremony they deserve as soon as restrictions and guidance allow. Thank you for your patience and understanding. Updated information will be provided as it is received. We remain immeasurably proud of these graduates and their achievements.

post_text: The draft re-entry plan for this fall is set to be released next Monday, July 13. Right now, we have information on our website about some of the guidelines we are following, including recommendations from the American Academy o pediatrics, the CDC, and the Jefferson County Health Department. Workgroups made up of dozens of stakeholders, including teachers and community members, used that information over many weeks to develop safe ways to get back into classrooms. We need your feedback about how the schedule should be adjusted to accommodate enhanced cleaning techniques our custodians will use to protect everyone. Those techniques will be also be outlined in more detail in the draft plan. Please visit our website and take part in the ongoing ThoughtExchange conversation.

post_text: Students in Jefferson County will be back in school five days a week as part of the JCS Re-entry Plan. The plan prioritizes student safety and will continue to adhere to the latest guidance from the CDC, the American Academy of Pediatrics, and the Jefferson County Health Department. Specific information will be available early next week. Please help us continue to meet the needs of our students by participating in JCS ThoughtExchange. Visit our website for regular updates.

Specific information will be available early next week. Please help us continue to meet the needs of our students by participating in JCS ThoughtExchange. Visit our website for regular updates.

post_text:
Earlier this month, JCS hit a milestone. Since March 13, when school facilities and buildings closed due to the COVID-19 Pandemic, employee volunteers have provided more than 100,000 meals to our students. It is an incredible accomplishment, and the good news continues for Jefferson County families. The JCS Child Nutrition Program will continue through the summer!
Five-day meal kits will continue to be delivered weekly from June 2 through August 4, 2020. JCS is continuing to work with Kilmer’s Farm Market to assemble and deliver food every TUESDAY from 11:00 AM to 12:00 PM. Sites will be reduced due to the changing logistics of the summer months, but the amount of food will remain the same. The following schools will serve as pick-up locations:

· Blue Ridge Elementary School 18866 Charles Town Rd

· North Jefferson Elementary School 6996 Charles Town Rd

· Wright Denny Intermediate School 209 West Congress Street

· Washington High School 300 Washington Patriot Drive

post_text:
Jefferson County Schools (JCS) understands that many of our students are ready to experience one of the great transitions of adolescence and obtain their driver's license. As you know, getting a driver's license requires that you provide proof of enrollment from our schools. Knowing the importance of this rite of passage, we are executing the following plan to support our students:

1. JCS has 2,080 students who meet the criteria to obtain their license and require an enrollment form to do so.

2. Our staff have completed a download, batch printing, and a sort and mail post process for all eligible students. All enrollment forms for eligible students will be mailed by May 26, 2020, for arrival by June 1, 2020.

3. The WV DMV is currently slated to re-open on Tuesday, May 26, 2020, by appointment ONLY. We strongly suggest you make an appointment June 1, 2020, or later to accommodate the US Mail delivery schedule.

Thank you for your continued support and trust in serving your children.

We are pleased to share the news that Jefferson High School and Washington High School are working on a joint project to create yard banners for the Class of 2020! The banners will feature the school name and logo, the student’s name, and their senior picture.
The banners will be posted at both schools for our original graduation weekend. Seniors are invited for a drive-through Senior Celebration Parade on Sunday, May 17th. The parade at Washington High School will be held at 2pm and Jefferson High School at 4pm. Students and their families can drive through and view the signs as we all show their support for one another. Feel free to wear your cap and gown, decorate your car, and honk and wave, but please remain in your car during the parade.
Seniors are invited to come back by the school any time the following week to pick up their own banner to have as a keepsake. Please be mindful to social distance if others are present. 2

post_text:
Washington High School teachers and staff didn’t let Covid-19 stop them from celebrating the 50th Anniversary of Earth Day on April 22.
Many of the staff had ordered customized shirts before the closure of school buildings and facilities and even got their families and pets involved.
Some of the activities they did Thursday to celebrate included picking up trash along the roadside near their homes, recycling, taking a walk, pledging to reduce or eliminate the use of plastics (especially plastic water bottles), switching to shampoo & conditioner that is in bar form, and making bird feeders and crafts out of recycled materials with their own children. #OneJefferson

WVU Virtual Game Design Club!

In this 4-week club, youth will learn basic video game coding concepts by making different types of games (including racing, platform, and launching games) using CS First and Scratch. The club is designed for new and beginner coders who are currently in 4th - 8th grade. The club will meet virtually twice a week for one hour (Tuesdays and Thursdays from 3:30-4:30 PM EST) starting May 5th and ending May 28th. Space is limited, register online now!

West Virginia Parent Training and Information (WVPTI) is conducting a community need assessment focused on West Virginia parents and caregivers of children with special needs. The survey will help us identify the current and specific needs of families as a result of the COVID-19 pandemic. Your responses will inform our program planning during this crisis and will foster collaborating opportunities with state and private agencies to better meet your needs.
Our goal is to obtain high-quality feedback from a diverse and wide variety of perspectives across the state.
It should only take 10 minutes or less to complete the survey.
We hope you will participate and encourage others to do so, too. Please share!
You can take the survey here!

The Sheetz Store in Kearneysville will be participating in a new Kidz Meal Bagz program that will provide free food to help children and families in need as a result of the COVID-19 pandemic. Meal Bagz will be available all day starting Thursday, April 2 and will include a turkey sandwich, chips, and a drink.

Families interested in taking advantage of the free Kidz Meal Bagz program should go to participating Sheetz locations and ask an employee at the register for a meal. Families will be offered one bag per child. Meals will be available daily while supplies last.

post_text: March 25, 2020: Tonight would have been our annual Jefferson County Schools Teacher and School Service Person of the Year dinner. We had planned to gather as a community and celebrate Media Specialist at C.W. Shipley, Lauren Walls, and Cafeteria Manager at Charles Town Middle, Kelli Myers. While we are sad not to be together physically, we are together in spirit. The work all of our staff have done in the last two weeks is overwhelming. We are truly blessed to have these individuals serving students in Jefferson County. Despite the disruption, we are excited to honor Lauren and Kelli this year. We wish them luck when they compete at the state level later this year! Thank you for representing Jefferson County Schools!

post_text:
Dear Jefferson County Families,

I hope you are well as our community continues to navigate these uncertain times. Jefferson County Schools employees have spent hundreds of hours volunteering to pack and deliver food to students throughout the county. As the situation with the COVID-19 Pandemic continues, we are taking additional steps to not only keep students safe and fed but to protect our staff as well. On Monday, March 23, 2020, five days' worth of food will be made available at these sites to serve our school community. The food packs can be picked up between 11:00 AM and Noon and are available to ANY CHILD IN THE COUNTY. Sending multi-day packs requires less exposure for everyone while we uphold our long term commitment to families and staff until this pandemic passes. Thank you for your continued trust and support and thank you to our staff who have continued to support kids.

Dear Jefferson County Families,

I hope you are well as our community continues to navigate these uncertain times. Jefferson County Schools employees have spent hundreds of hours volunteering to pack and deliver food to students throughout the county. As the situation with the COVID-19 Pandemic continues, we are taking additional steps to not only keep students safe and fed but to protect our staff as well. On Monday, March 23, 2020, five days' worth of food will be made available at these sites to serve our school community. The food packs can be picked up between 11:00 AM and Noon and are available to ANY CHILD IN THE COUNTY. Sending multi-day packs requires less exposure for everyone while we uphold our long term commitment to families and staff until this pandemic passes. Thank you for your continued trust and support and thank you to our staff who have continued to support kids.

105 W. John St.
(304) 263-2696
Pick up will occur in the back parking lot.

Visit the JCS Website for more about child nutrition during the closure.

post_text: Jefferson County Schools puts the safety and wellbeing of students and staff first. That standard is true as we address COVID-19. Our school district has been closely monitoring the spread of COVID-19 in the United States and is following the guidance of the Jefferson County Health Department and other partner agencies. We have been working with public health officials and will continue to follow their expert recommendations to best ensure the safety of the students and families we serve. Handling the Corona Virus will be very similar to how we deal with any contagious disease. We will partner with these and other agencies and will follow the guidelines laid out in the Jefferson County Schools Pandemic Response Plan, available on our website.

post_text: Booker T. Washington was an American educator, author, orator, and advisor to multiple U.S. Presidents, but he was born a slave in 1856! After putting himself through school, Washington went on to become one of the foremost African American leaders of the late 19th and early 20th centuries, founding the Tuskegee Normal and Industrial Institute (now Tuskegee University) in 1881.
